{"title_page": "Pelli Choopulu", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 film by Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pelli Choopulu\n| image          = Pelli Choopulu poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam]]\n| producer       = {{Unbulleted list\n  | Raj Kandukuri\n  | Yash Rangineni<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/today/pellichoopulu-29july.html |title=D.Suresh babu presents \"Pelli Choopulu\" Releasing on July 29th |publisher=Idlebrain.com |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n  }}\n| screenplay     = Tharun Bhaskar Dhaassyam\n| story          = Tharun Bhaskar Dhaassyam\n| starring       = {{Unbulleted list\n  | [[Vijay Deverakonda]]\n  | [[Ritu Varma]]\n    }}\n| music          = [[Vivek Sagar]]\n| cinematography = Nagesh Banell\n| editing        = Ravi Teja Girijala\n| studio         = BigBen Cinemas(London) & Dharmapatha Creations\n| distributor    = [[Suresh Productions]] [Overseas by FreezeFrameFilms]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2016|07|29}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| budget         = \u20b9 2 Crore<ref name=\"Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianmoviestats.com/|title=Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats|website=www.indianmoviestats.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n| gross          = \u20b9 27 Crore<ref name=\"Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianmoviestats.com/|title=Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats|website=www.indianmoviestats.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Pelli Choopulu''''' ({{trans|[[Matchmaking]]}}) is a 2016 Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu-language]] [[romantic comedy]] film written and directed by [[Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam]] and produced by Raj Kandukuri and Yash Rangineni. It features [[Vijay Deverakonda]] and [[Ritu Varma]] in the lead roles. Partly based on real life incident of \"Spitfire BBQ\" food truck,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chaibisket.com/real-life-pellichoopulu-couple/|title=Meet The Real-Life Couple Who Inspired The Lead Characters Of Pelli Choopulu!|last=Pasha|first=Gouse|date=|website=Chai Bisket|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> the film revolves around a boy and a girl who meet during a match-making and how their aspirations bring them together forms the rest of the story.\n\nThe film was released worldwide on 29 July 2016 to positive reviews from critics and became a commercial success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/Pelli-Choopulu-review-A-Refreshing-and-realistic-love-story/2016/07/29/article3553338.ece |title='Pelli Choopulu' review: A Refreshing and realistic love story |newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]] |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/pelli-choopulu-review-a-gem-of-a-film/article8917019.ece |title=Pelli Choopulu review: A gem of a film |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref> The film provided breakthrough for the film's cast and crew.\n\nThe film won two [[National Film Awards]] for [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu|Best Telugu film]], and [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay \u2013 Dialogues]], two [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]], and the [[6th South Indian International Movie Awards|SIIMA Award for Best Film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/nani-and-jr-ntr-walk-away-with-top-honours-at-siima-2017/articleshow/59397205.cms |title=Nani and Jr NTR bag top honours at SIIMA-2017 &#124; Telugu Movie News |work=The Times of India |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=6 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"64thaward\">{{cite press release|title=64th National Film Awards|url=http://www.dff.nic.in/writereaddata/NFA64PressNote2016.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|accessdate=7 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606051143/http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/NFA64PressNote2016.pdf|archivedate=6 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was remade in [[Hindi]] as ''[[Mitron]]'' (2018) and in [[Malayalam]] as ''[[Vijay Superum Pournamiyum]]'' (2019).\n\n==Plot==\nPrasanth ([[Vijay Deverakonda]]) goes to Chitra's ([[Ritu Varma]]) house for a matchmaking event. He is a guy who completes his BTech by clearing many subjects for almost 5 years, but he is also lazy and incapable of doing any work. His dream is to become a chef and open a restaurant, but he doesn't get any support from his father. Chitra is a very focused girl who works hard to fulfill her dreams of going to Australia. However, her father shows no interest, as she is a girl. When both of them meet at the matchmaking event her younger cousin, Subhash, accidentally locks the door. To pass time, they talk about their past.\n\nChitra reveals that she was in love with a North Indian guy named Vikram. They both wanted to start a food van business. Vikram went to Delhi to talk with his father about their love and business. Meanwhile, Chitra started her plan eagerly, and was ready to surprise Vikram by buying the van. Then things went wrong and Vikram did not come back overpowered by greed of getting dowry. Chitra and her father waited for him but when they realised Vikram wasn't coming back, her father decided to get her married to someone else.\n\nOn his turn, Prasanth reveals that he was unemployed and always went out with his two friends. He, along with his friends, made cooking videos, as he is passionate about cooking. But it wasn't profitable enough so, they plan to make prank videos and were caught red-handed by Prashant's father, which ended their plan. He then got a job in a call centre after he was recommended by his father. He started going out with a girl to show off to his friends, but she cheated on him. He found out about it only when her second boyfriend called him at work, and quit his job after having a fight with his boss.\n\nIt is then revealed that Prasanth came to the wrong address for his matchmaking event. Later, Prasanth goes to his actual matchmaking event, which was with a rich family. Meanwhile, Chitra tells the guy coming to her matchmaking event that she's not interested in marriage. The family of Prasanth's bride wanted him to be able to run a business, so he and Chitra decide to operate the food truck themselves, with Prasanth as the chef, and Chitra in charge of the business side of things. At first, they face many difficulties, mainly through Prasanth's and his friends' laziness as well as fighting with Chitra and giving up the food van idea.\n\nPrasanth visits Chitra's house and informs her father that he should be proud to have such a responsible daughter. He also claims that if he ever gets a child he would wish to have daughter like Chitra and insists him that he let her pursue her dreams. Chitra understands the good nature of Prasanth and later convinces his father that he is a natural cook by cooking them Prasanth's recipe. They kickstart their business with the support from both their parents. After this, their food van becomes a smashing success. In the process, they fall in love without realizing it, but both of them are engaged to other people, so they drift apart. After realizing they love each other, they come back together through a radio show organised by their friend, with the support of their family and friends.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vijay Deverakonda]] as Prasanth\n* [[Ritu Varma]] as Chitra\n* [[Priyadarshi Pullikonda|Priyadarshi]] as Kaushik\n* Abhay Bethiganti as Vishnu\n* Nandu as Vikram\n* [[Anish Kuruvilla]] as Businessman\n* Kedar Shankara as Prashant's Father\n* Yogi Khathri as Event Manager\n* Padmaja Lanka as Prashanth's Mother\n* Gururaj Manepalli as Chitra's Father\n* Sujata Gosukonda as Chitra's Mother\n* Anisha Alla as Prashanth's Ex-Girlfriend\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAfter making numerous short films, Tharun Bhascker made his directorial debut with this film.<ref name = ib/> According to Tharun, ''Pelli Choopulu'' \"is a very urban comedy set in a middle class in Hyderabad. It shows the contrast between the old and young generations and the comedy of errors that can happen within the space.\"<ref name = hi>https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/after-short-films-tarun-bhasker-to-direct-a-feature/article7936817.ece</ref> Tharun had this basic idea of two contrasting personalities meeting for match-making, both getting stuck in a room is a metaphor for dating while food truck is a metaphor for live-in relationship.<ref name = ib/>\n\n===Casting===\nRitu Verma who earlier worked in Tharun's ''[[Sainma]]'' was selected as lead actress while Vijay Deverakonda who portrayed a supporting role in [[Yevade Subramanyam|''Yevade Subramaniam'' (2015)]] made his debut as lead actor with this film.<ref>http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Cinema/2016-04-30/From-YouTube-to-70MM/225117</ref> Vijay agreed to do this role as he found it \"realistically very lazy\" and \"so close to my heart because young attitude, irresponsible behavior was a part of my personal life\".<ref name = vd>http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/vijaydevarakonda.html</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nTharun shot the entire film in [[sync sound]] as he feels it offers freedom for artists to improvise their dialogues. The sync sound equipment from Mumbai, that was used for ''[[Gangs of Wasseypur|Gangs Of Wasseypur]]'' was used for this film.<ref name = hi/> The filming was completed within 35 days.<ref name = vd/>\n\n===Themes and influences===\nTharun followed character arcs from [[Knocked Up]] (directed by [[Judd Apatow]]). For the food truck business thread, Tharun revealed he drew inspirations from films like ''[[The Hundred-Foot Journey (film)|100 foot journey]]'' and ''[[Chef (2014 film)|Chef]]''.<ref name = ib>http://www.idlebrain.com/movie/postmortem/pellichoopulu.html</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThis film has six songs composed by [[Vivek Sagar]] and lyrics are written by [[Rahul Ramakrishna]], [[Shreshta]], Shri, & Nikhil Bharadwaj. Music released on [[Madhura Audio]].\n\nVivek Sagar earlier composed music for Tharun Bhascker's short film ''Sainma'', he revealed that the film's music was conceived only after the film was shot.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/engineer-turned-composer-vivek-sagar-revels-in-the-joy-of-making-music/article19660463.ece</ref> \"With no lip sync songs, the music blended in with the narrative\", he said.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/Eclecticism-his-signature/article14511348.ece</ref>\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Pelli choopulu\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| longtype   = to Pelli choopulu\n| artist     = Vivek Sagar\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 29 July 2016\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Tapeloop\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 19:18\n| language   = [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| label      = [[Madhura Audio]]\n| producer   = Vivek Sagar\n| prev_title = '''[[Race (2013 film)|Race]]'''\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title =''[[Yuddham Sharanam]]''\n| next_year  =2017\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed =\n| headline = Track listing\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| total_length = 19:18\n| title1 = Ee Babu Gariki \n| note1 =\n| lyrics1 = Rahul Ramakrishna\n| extra1 = [[Sooraj Santhosh]]\n| length1 = 3:10\n| title2 = Chinuku Taake\n| note2 =\n| lyrics2 = [[Shreshta]]\n| extra2 = Amritavarshini KC\n| length2 = 4:38\n| title3 = Raalu Raaga Poolamala\n| note3 =\n| lyrics3 = Rahul Ramakrishna, Shri\n| extra3 = Shri, Wilson Herald\n| length3 = 3:23\n| title4 = Merise Merise\n| note4 =\n| lyrics4 = Shreshta\n| extra4 = [[Haricharan]], Pranavi Acharya\n| length4 = 5.04\n| title5 = Aanandamayenu\n| note5 =\n| lyrics5 = [[Instrumental]]\n| extra5 = Tejas Mallela (violin), Ranjani Sivakumar (singer)\n| length5 = 1:41\n| title6 = Spitfire Friends \n| note6 =\n| lyrics6 = Nikhil Bharadwaj\n| extra6 = Nikhil Bharadwaj\n| length6 = 3:22\n}}\n\n==Awards==\n'''[[National Film Awards]]'''\n\n*[[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu|Best Feature Film in Telugu]] \u2013 Dharmapatha Creations & BigBen Cinemas\n*[[National Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] \u2013 Dialogues \u2013 Tharun Bahascker Dassyam\n \n;[[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/winners-64th-jio-filmfare-awards-south/articleshow/59192157.cms|title=Winners: 64th Jio Filmfare Awards 2017 (South).|website=India Today|date=2018-06-16|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Film - Telugu|Best Film \u2013 Telugu]] \u2013 Yash Rangineni & Raj Kandukuri\n* [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actor - South|Critics Best Actress \u2013 Telugu]] \u2013 [[Ritu Varma]]\n\n;[[South Indian International Movie Awards|SIIMA Awards]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/siima-awards-2017-telugu-winners-list-jr-ntr-rakul-preet-singh-declared-best-actors-733067|title=SIIMA Awards 2017 Telugu winners list: Jr NTR and Rakul Preet Singh declared best actors|website=International Business Times|date=2017-07-02|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n*[[6th South Indian International Movie Awards|Best Film]]\n\n;[[Nandi Awards]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/13-nandi-awards-for-baahubali/articleshow/61655551.cms|title=Andhra Pradesh government announces Nandi|website=The Times of India|date=2017-11-15|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n* [[Nandi Award for Best Feature Film|Best Film]] (Gold)  \u2013 Dharmapatha Creations & BigBen Cinemas\n* [[Nandi Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] \u2013 [[Ritu Varma]]\n\n== Remakes ==\n''Pelli Choopulu'' was remade in [[Hindi]] as ''[[Mitron]]'' (2018),<ref>http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/review/2018/sep/21/mitron-movie-review-a-hit-and-a-miss-kind-of-film-1875355.html</ref> and in [[Malayalam]] as ''[[Vijay Superum Pournamiyum]]'' (2019).<ref>http://www.sify.com/movies/vijay-superum-pournamiyum-review-a-watchable-romantic-comedy-review-malayalam-tbmn9bhicabje.html</ref> In 2016, [[Gautham Menon]] bought the remake rights for [[Tamil language|Tamil]],<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/pelli-choopulu-tamil-remake-rights-acquired-by-gautham-menon-348659-2016-10-26</ref> but the version, titled ''Pon Ondru Kandein'', failed to take off.<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/vishnu-vishal-tamannaah-pelli-choopulu-remake-shelved-gautham-menon-reveals-1289983-2018-07-19</ref> The film is being remade in Tamil by debutante Kaarthikk Sundar starring [[Harish Kalyan]] and [[Priya Bhavani Shankar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/harish-kalyan-to-star-in-pelli-choopulu-tamil-remake/article30275260.ece|title=Harish Kalyan to star in \u2018Pelli Choopulu\u2019 Tamil remake|date=11 December 2019|work=The Hindu|author=Pradeep Kumar}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|5824826}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Feature Film Telugu|state=collapsed}}\n{{Filmfare Best Telugu Film}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Telangana]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about Indian weddings]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Dialogue National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Best Telugu Feature Film National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2016 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2016 film by Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pelli Choopulu\n| image          = Pelli Choopulu poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam]]\n| producer       = {{Unbulleted list\n  | Raj Kandukuri\n  | Yash Rangineni<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/today/pellichoopulu-29july.html |title=D.Suresh babu presents \"Pelli Choopulu\" Releasing on July 29th |publisher=Idlebrain.com |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n  }}\n| screenplay     = Tharun Bhaskar Dhaassyam\n| story          = Tharun Bhaskar Dhaassyam\n| starring       = {{Unbulleted list\n  | [[Vijay Deverakonda]]\n  | [[Ritu Varma]]\n    }}\n| music          = [[Vivek Sagar]]\n| cinematography = Nagesh Banell\n| editing        = Ravi Teja Girijala\n| studio         = BigBen Cinemas(London) & Dharmapatha Creations\n| distributor    = [[Suresh Productions]] [Overseas by FreezeFrameFilms]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2016|07|29}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| budget         = \u20b9 2 Crore<ref name=\"Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianmoviestats.com/|title=Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats|website=www.indianmoviestats.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n| gross          = \u20b9 27 Crore<ref name=\"Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianmoviestats.com/|title=Pelli Choopulu - IndianMovieStats|website=www.indianmoviestats.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Pelli Choopulu''''' ({{trans|[[Matchmaking]]}}) is a 2016 Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu-language]] [[romantic comedy]] film written and directed by [[Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam]] and produced by Raj Kandukuri and Yash Rangineni. It features [[Vijay Deverakonda]] and [[Ritu Varma]] in the lead roles. Partly based on real life incident of \"Spitfire BBQ\" food truck,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chaibisket.com/real-life-pellichoopulu-couple/|title=Meet The Real-Life Couple Who Inspired The Lead Characters Of Pelli Choopulu!|last=Pasha|first=Gouse|date=|website=Chai Bisket|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> the film revolves around a boy and a girl who meet during a match-making and how their aspirations bring them together forms the rest of the story.\n\nThe film was released worldwide on 29 July 2016 to positive reviews from critics and became a commercial success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/Pelli-Choopulu-review-A-Refreshing-and-realistic-love-story/2016/07/29/article3553338.ece |title='Pelli Choopulu' review: A Refreshing and realistic love story |newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]] |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/pelli-choopulu-review-a-gem-of-a-film/article8917019.ece |title=Pelli Choopulu review: A gem of a film |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref> The film provided breakthrough for the film's cast and crew.\n\nThe film won two [[National Film Awards]] for [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu|Best Telugu film]], and [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay \u2013 Dialogues]], two [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]], and the [[6th South Indian International Movie Awards|SIIMA Award for Best Film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/nani-and-jr-ntr-walk-away-with-top-honours-at-siima-2017/articleshow/59397205.cms |title=Nani and Jr NTR bag top honours at SIIMA-2017 &#124; Telugu Movie News |work=The Times of India |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=6 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"64thaward\">{{cite press release|title=64th National Film Awards|url=http://www.dff.nic.in/writereaddata/NFA64PressNote2016.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|accessdate=7 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606051143/http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/NFA64PressNote2016.pdf|archivedate=6 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was remade in [[Hindi]] as ''[[Mitron]]'' (2018) and in [[Malayalam]] as ''[[Vijay Superum Pournamiyum]]'' (2019).\n\n==Plot==\nPrasanth ([[Vijay Deverakonda]]) goes to Chitra's ([[Ritu Varma]]) house for a matchmaking event. He is a guy who completes his BTech by clearing many subjects for almost 5 years, but he is also lazy and incapable of doing any work. His dream is to become a chef and open a restaurant, but he doesn't get any support from his father. Chitra is a very focused girl who works hard to fulfill her dreams of going to Australia. However, her father shows no interest, as she is a girl. When both of them meet at the matchmaking event her younger cousin, Subhash, accidentally locks the door and they get stuck. To pass time, they talk about their past.\n\nChitra reveals that she was in love with a North Indian guy named Vikram. They both wanted to start a food truck business. Vikram went to Delhi to talk with his father about their love and business. Meanwhile, Chitra started her plan eagerly, and was ready to surprise Vikram by buying the truck. Then things went wrong and Vikram did not come back overpowered by greed of getting dowry. Chitra and her father waited for him but when they realised Vikram wasn't coming back, her father decided to get her married to someone else.\n\nOn his turn, Prasanth reveals that he was unemployed and always went out with his two friends. He, along with his friends, made cooking videos, as he is passionate about cooking. But it wasn't profitable enough so, they plan to make prank videos and were caught red-handed by Prashant's father, which ended their plan. He then got a job in a call centre after he was recommended by his father. He started going out with a girl to show off to his friends, but she cheated on him. He found out about it only when her second boyfriend called him at work, and quit his job after having a fight with his boss.\n\nIt is then revealed that Prasanth came to the wrong address for his matchmaking event. Later, Prasanth goes to his actual matchmaking event, which was with a rich family. Meanwhile, Chitra tells the guy coming to her matchmaking event that she's not interested in marriage. The family of Prasanth's bride wanted him to be able to run a business, so he and Chitra decide to operate the food truck themselves, with Prasanth as the chef, and Chitra in charge of the business side of things. At first, they face many difficulties, mainly through Prasanth's and his friends' laziness as well as fighting with Chitra and giving up the food truck.\n\nPrasanth visits Chitra's house and informs her father that he should be proud to have such a responsible daughter. He also claims that if he ever gets a child he would wish to have daughter like Chitra and insists him that he let her pursue her dreams. Chitra understands the good nature of Prasanth and later convinces his father that he is a natural cook by cooking them Prasanth's recipe. They kickstart their business with the support from both their parents. After this, their food truck becomes a smashing success. In the process, they fall in love without realizing it, but both of them are engaged to other people, so they drift apart. After realizing they love each other, they come back together through a radio show organised by their friend, with the support of their family and friends.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vijay Deverakonda]] as Prasanth\n* [[Ritu Varma]] as Chitra\n* [[Priyadarshi Pullikonda|Priyadarshi]] as Kaushik\n* Abhay Bethiganti as Vishnu\n* Nandu as Vikram\n* [[Anish Kuruvilla]] as Businessman\n* Kedar Shankara as Prashant's Father\n* Yogi Khathri as Event Manager\n* Padmaja Lanka as Prashanth's Mother\n* Gururaj Manepalli as Chitra's Father\n* Sujata Gosukonda as Chitra's Mother\n* Anisha Alla as Prashanth's Ex-Girlfriend\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAfter making numerous short films, Tharun Bhascker made his directorial debut with this film.<ref name = ib/> According to Tharun, ''Pelli Choopulu'' \"is a very urban comedy set in a middle class in Hyderabad. It shows the contrast between the old and young generations and the comedy of errors that can happen within the space.\"<ref name = hi>https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/after-short-films-tarun-bhasker-to-direct-a-feature/article7936817.ece</ref> Tharun had this basic idea of two contrasting personalities meeting for match-making, both getting stuck in a room is a metaphor for dating while food truck is a metaphor for live-in relationship.<ref name = ib/>\n\n===Casting===\nRitu Verma who earlier worked in Tharun's ''[[Sainma]]'' was selected as lead actress while Vijay Deverakonda who portrayed a supporting role in [[Yevade Subramanyam|''Yevade Subramaniam'' (2015)]] made his debut as lead actor with this film.<ref>http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Cinema/2016-04-30/From-YouTube-to-70MM/225117</ref> Vijay agreed to do this role as he found it \"realistically very lazy\" and \"so close to my heart because young attitude, irresponsible behavior was a part of my personal life\".<ref name = vd>http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/vijaydevarakonda.html</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nTharun shot the entire film in [[sync sound]] as he feels it offers freedom for artists to improvise their dialogues. The sync sound equipment from Mumbai, that was used for ''[[Gangs of Wasseypur|Gangs Of Wasseypur]]'' was used for this film.<ref name = hi/> The filming was completed within 35 days.<ref name = vd/>\n\n===Themes and influences===\nTharun followed character arcs from [[Knocked Up]] (directed by [[Judd Apatow]]). For the food truck business thread, Tharun revealed he drew inspirations from films like ''[[The Hundred-Foot Journey (film)|100 foot journey]]'' and ''[[Chef (2014 film)|Chef]]''.<ref name = ib>http://www.idlebrain.com/movie/postmortem/pellichoopulu.html</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThis film has six songs composed by [[Vivek Sagar]] and lyrics are written by [[Rahul Ramakrishna]], [[Shreshta]], Shri, & Nikhil Bharadwaj. Music released on [[Madhura Audio]].\n\nVivek Sagar earlier composed music for Tharun Bhascker's short film ''Sainma'', he revealed that the film's music was conceived only after the film was shot.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/engineer-turned-composer-vivek-sagar-revels-in-the-joy-of-making-music/article19660463.ece</ref> \"With no lip sync songs, the music blended in with the narrative\", he said.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/Eclecticism-his-signature/article14511348.ece</ref>\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Pelli choopulu\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| longtype   = to Pelli choopulu\n| artist     = Vivek Sagar\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 29 July 2016\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Tapeloop\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 19:18\n| language   = [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| label      = [[Madhura Audio]]\n| producer   = Vivek Sagar\n| prev_title = '''[[Race (2013 film)|Race]]'''\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title =''[[Yuddham Sharanam]]''\n| next_year  =2017\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed =\n| headline = Track listing\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| total_length = 19:18\n| title1 = Ee Babu Gariki \n| note1 =\n| lyrics1 = Rahul Ramakrishna\n| extra1 = [[Sooraj Santhosh]]\n| length1 = 3:10\n| title2 = Chinuku Taake\n| note2 =\n| lyrics2 = [[Shreshta]]\n| extra2 = Amritavarshini KC\n| length2 = 4:38\n| title3 = Raalu Raaga Poolamala\n| note3 =\n| lyrics3 = Rahul Ramakrishna, Shri\n| extra3 = Shri, Wilson Herald\n| length3 = 3:23\n| title4 = Merise Merise\n| note4 =\n| lyrics4 = Shreshta\n| extra4 = [[Haricharan]], Pranavi Acharya\n| length4 = 5.04\n| title5 = Aanandamayenu\n| note5 =\n| lyrics5 = [[Instrumental]]\n|